===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
[[File:晚商作册般青铜鼋.jpg|thumb|X-ray image of the ''Zuoceban yuan'' inscription, Late Shang dynasty]]
Earliest attested on the late Shang bronze {{lw|zh|作册般銅黿}}. {{Han compound|水|alt1=氵|廌|盍|t1=water|t2=a type of antelope or caprid|c1=s|c2=s|c3=p|abb3=y|ls=psc|nocap=y|tr=*pap|tr3=*gˤap}}. Later, {{lang|zh|廌}} was omitted.

In bronze inscriptions, mostly used for {{och-l|廢|to cast aside; to waste|tr=*pas}}:
{{zh-x|率 亡 '''@灋'''{fèi} 矢。|not a single arrow was '''wasted'''.|CL-PC|ref=Late {{w|Shang dynasty|Shang}}, {{lw|zh|作册般銅黿}} inscription|collapsed=y}}

A notable exception is the early Western Zhou {{lw|zh|大盂鼎}}, where [[灋]] is analyzed as [[廢]] in the sense of "great" (per {{w|Erya}} {{lang|zh|《釋詁》：「廢，[[大]]也。」}}):
{{zh-x|…故 天 異 臨 子、'''@灋''' 保 先王、☐ 有 四方。|...therefore Heaven watched over you with extraordinary [favour], '''greatly''' safeguarded the former kings, and [they] possessed the four quarters.|CL-PC|ref=Early {{w|Western Zhou}}, {{w|Da Yu ding}} inscription|collapsed=y}}

===Etymology 1===
{{der|zh|sit}}. Cognate with {{cog|bo|བབས||shape, form, appearance}}, {{m|bo|དབྱིབས||shape, form, figure}}, {{cog|my|ပုံ||shape, form}}. Possibly cognate with {{och-l|凡|all, general, every; pattern, general rule}}; see there for more.

